1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,529
One of the reviewers of an early version of this book is a close personal friend who owns his own business management consulting firm.

2
00:00:08,960 --> 00:00:15,970
When he read the above illustration, he commented, That's the positive result of liking and respecting people.

3
00:00:16,240 --> 00:00:23,650
Let me give you a personal experience of a friend of mine which shows what happens if you don't like and admire people.

4
00:00:24,080 --> 00:00:26,370
His experience has a big point.

5
00:00:26,480 --> 00:00:27,650
Here it is.

6
00:00:28,240 --> 00:00:36,049
My firm obtained a contract to provide consulting services to a relatively small soft drink bottling concern.

7
00:00:36,320 --> 00:00:38,289
The contract was substantial.

8
00:00:38,400 --> 00:00:41,089
The client had little formal education.

9
00:00:41,279 --> 00:00:47,329
His business was in bad shape, and in recent years he had made some very costly mistakes.

10
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:53,809
Three days after we had got the contract, an associate and I were driving out to his plant,

11
00:00:53,840 --> 00:00:57,010
which was about 45 minutes from our offices.

12
00:00:57,440 --> 00:01:04,930
To this day I don't know how it started, but somehow we began talking about the negative qualities of our client.

13
00:01:05,279 --> 00:01:11,890
Before we realized it, we were talking about how his own stupidity had brought about the mess he was in,

14
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:16,690
instead of discussing how we could best approach solving his problems.

15
00:01:17,200 --> 00:01:21,250
I remember one remark I made which I thought particularly clever.

16
00:01:21,520 --> 00:01:25,089
The only thing holding up Mr. F is fat.

17
00:01:25,440 --> 00:01:30,049
My associate laughed and came up with an equally choice observation.

18
00:01:30,400 --> 00:01:39,970
And that son of his, Junior must be all of thirty-five, but the only qualification he has for the job he's holding is he speaks English.

19
00:01:40,720 --> 00:01:47,490
The whole drive out, we talked about nothing else but what a weak-minded numbskull we had as a client.

20
00:01:48,080 --> 00:01:51,170
Well, the conference that afternoon was cold.

21
00:01:51,360 --> 00:01:56,130
Looking back, I think our client sensed somehow the way we felt toward him.

22
00:01:56,400 --> 00:02:04,849
He must have thought, these fellows think I'm stupid or something, and all they're going to do for my money is give me some smooth-sounding talk.

23
00:02:05,520 --> 00:02:09,170
Two days later, I got a two-sentence letter from this client.

24
00:02:09,200 --> 00:02:14,210
It said, I've decided to cancel our contract for your consulting services.

25
00:02:14,320 --> 00:02:18,450
If there is a charge for your services to date, please bill me.

26
00:02:19,039 --> 00:02:24,690
Printing ourselves with negative thoughts for only 40 minutes cost us a contract.

27
00:02:24,880 --> 00:02:35,089
What made it even more painful was learning, about a month later, that this former client had contracted with an out-of-town firm for the professional assistance he needed.

28
00:02:35,920 --> 00:02:40,930
We would never have lost him had we concentrated on his many fine qualities.

29
00:02:41,039 --> 00:02:42,370
And he has them.

30
00:02:42,560 --> 00:02:43,970
Most people do.

31
00:02:44,720 --> 00:02:50,690
Here's how you can have some fun and discover a basic success principle at the same time.

32
00:02:50,960 --> 00:02:55,730
For the next two days, listen in on as many conversations as you can.

33
00:02:55,920 --> 00:02:57,250
Note two things.

34
00:02:57,520 --> 00:03:04,049
Which person in the conversation does the most talking, and which person is the more successful?

35
00:03:04,960 --> 00:03:08,370
Hundreds of my own little experiments have revealed this.

36
00:03:08,640 --> 00:03:15,490
The person who does the most talking and the person who is the most successful are rarely the same person.

37
00:03:15,840 --> 00:03:23,490
Almost without exception, the more successful the person, the more he practices conversation generosity,

38
00:03:23,520 --> 00:03:28,610
that is, he encourages the other person to talk about himself, his views,

39
00:03:28,640 --> 00:03:33,170
his accomplishments, his family, his job, his problems.

40
00:03:33,680 --> 00:03:39,329
Conversation generosity paves the way to greater success in two important ways.

41
00:03:39,920 --> 00:03:43,809
One, conversation generosity wins friends.

42
00:03:44,560 --> 00:03:49,569
Two, conversation generosity helps you learn more about people.

43
00:03:51,120 --> 00:03:57,410
Remember this, the average person would rather talk about himself than anything else in this world.

